  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    org.culturegraph.mf.framework.LifeCycle, org.culturegraph.mf.framework.Sender<org.culturegraph.mf.framework.StreamReceiver>, org.culturegraph.mf.framework.StreamPipe<org.culturegraph.mf.framework.StreamReceiver>, org.culturegraph.mf.framework.StreamReceiver

    public class StreamUnflattener
extends org.culturegraph.mf.framework.DefaultStreamPipe<org.culturegraph.mf.framework.StreamReceiver>
    Reverse the effect of StreamFlattener The StreamFlattener is used by Metamorph and flattens out any hierarchical data into a flat list of key-value tuples. This class then constructs the flat structure produced by Metamorph and emits them in the proper hierarchy. So, one can use 'deep' output names in Metamorh (e.g. <data name="foo.bar%gt;), that pipe the result through an instance of StreamUnflattener and continue to work with the desired hierarchical structure.
    Author:
    Paul Horn

      • DEFAULT_INITIAL_DISCARD

        public static final java.lang.String DEFAULT_INITIAL_DISCARD
        Any entity at the root level, that value-equals this property will be discarded. The next entity will be the new root level of the resulting stream.

      • literal

        public void literal(java.lang.String name,
           java.lang.String value)
        Forwards the literal and emits some entity levels, if necessary. The parameter name is split on getEntityMarker(). The resulting array is interpreted as a path into a tree and according to the current state, some new nodes of this tree will be opened by calling startEntity and endEntity.
